#welcome
this tutorial explains how to use charts in slidenotes.io—click on the **play button** ![](playbutton.svg) for a preview of the presentation

and remember: you can always hit `escape` to look up the code structure of the slide, explore the menus and play around with the content.



---
## from data to charts

+++layout:left
*what's a chart?*
a graphical display of data.
*so what do you need to build one here in slidenotes?*
data and a chart block.
+++

+++layout: right
let's try ➡︎
+++

----
## the chart block

the code of a chart block looks like this:

+++code:none
 +++chart
 some data for the chart to display
 +++
+++

if you don't want to type the chart block in by hand, you can select it from the **toolbar** ![](toolbar.svg) on the right.

let's go and gather some data ➡︎

---
## simple sets of data

+++layout:left
let's say you installed a bird feeder at your window.
it was a big hit. and now you want to show off.
you want to build a chart that displays how your establishment  flourished over the course of a week due to beak to beak propaganda.

so what you'll have to do is gather sets of data.
each set containes information about how many birds visited on a particular day.
~day: number of birds~

now you put each set of data in each line of the chart container ➡︎
+++

---
## simple sets of data

+++layout:left
+++code
 +++chart
 monday: 1
 tuesday: 2
 wednesday: 5
 thursday: 9
 friday: 17
 +++
+++

these are the data sets displayed in your chart:
+++

+++layout:right
+++chart
monday: 1
tuesday: 2
wednesday: 5
thursday: 9
friday: 17
+++
+++

---
## different types of charts

+++layout: left
every pool of data has a chart type in which it's best displayed.
therefore we offer three different types of charts here at slidenotes:
**linear**, **bar** and **pie**.

as you just saw in the example, the linear type is our default one.
in order to change the type, you'll have to put in
~:bar~ or ~:pie~ next to ~+++chart~ in the header of the block.


+++code
 +++chart:bar
 data displayed in bar chart
 +++
+++


+++code
 +++chart:pie
 data displayed in pie chart
 +++
+++

let's check out some options ➡︎
+++

---
## different types of charts:
bar

+++layout:inline
so this is what happens
if we add ~:bar~
to the chart header
of our example from before:

+++chart:bar
monday: 1
tuesday: 2
wednesday: 5
thursday: 9
friday: 17
+++

+++code
 +++chart:bar
 monday: 1
 tuesday: 2
 wednesday: 5
 thursday: 9
 friday: 17
 +++
+++
+++

## different types of charts:
pie

+++layout:left
pie charts are the perfect choice whenever you want to show the individual share of single components forming a whole.
you see: because of the circular shape, numerical proportions can be illustrated as ...

wait a second!
we know what you're thinking!
"mhhhh... pie."

okay, let's cut the theory and bake us one ➡︎
+++

-----
## different types of charts:
pie

+++layout:left
###ingredients (in gram)

+++code
 +++chart:pie
 flour:300
 sugar:100
 butter:100
 baking powder:5
 apples:1000
 +++
+++

1. cut the apples
2. mix all other ingredients to a mass
3. layer up in a form: 2/3 of mass—apples—rest of mass as crumbles
4. put it in the oven for 40 minutes
+++

5. enjoy your pie while slidenotes bakes out your percentages

+++chart:pie
flour:300
sugar:100
butter:100
baking powder:10
apples:1000
+++

-----
## different types of charts:
the context menu

as you know, we offer three different types of charts: **linear**, **bar** and **pie**—but there's actually more.

for every type of chart, there is at least one alternative design, which displays the data in a slightly different way.

to check out all your possibilties, you can open the **chart context menu** ![](context-menu_chart.svg) which appears on the left side of your data whenever you click anywhere inside your ~+++chart~ container.

at the top of the menu, you'll find a symbol displaying the type of chart you are currently using. if you haven't specified your chart type yet, our **default line chart** ![](line chart symbol.png) will appear.
if you click on it, you can see the complete catalogue of chart options and select the one fitting your data the most.

-----
## different types of charts:
stack bar

+++layout:left
![](stack bar birds.svg)
+++

+++layout:right
one of the different chart types is the stack bar.

remember our bird feeding example?
good. let's stack that up!

spurred by your success from last week, you want to track the birds again.
only this time, you want to impress your new birdwatching friends from the internet.

so you sit down and you study the difference between sparrows and pigeons.

very proud of yourself, you want to show off your knowledge by counting and displaying them separately.

let's see what you should do ➡︎
+++

----
## different types of charts:
stack bar

+++layout:left
first, you build a chart container.

then, you either enter the **chart context menu** ![](context-menu_chart.svg)
to select the **stack bar** ![](stack bar symbol.png),

or you add the word ~:stackbar~ to the ~+++chart~ header.

while entering your data, you do just the same as before.
only now, you put in two numbers instead of just one.
~day: number of pigeons: number of sparrows~

+++code
 +++chart:stackbar
 monday: 9: 9
 tuesday: 10: 8
 wednesday: 11: 9
 +++
+++
+++

+++layout:right
+++chart:stackbar
monday: 9: 9
tuesday: 10: 8
wednesday: 11: 9
+++
+++

----
##elements of charts

+++layout:left
wow. leveling up bars to stack bars with one simple move.

why was that so easy, you ask?

because by making this move, you actually used a pretty powerful chart building tool:
it's called a separator.
and it's one of the three elements that every chart container needs:

- **identifiers**
- **values**
- **separators**

let's break down which does what ➡︎
+++

---
##elements of charts

here's what every element did in the case of our bird feeder example:

+++table
chart element; code in example; function in slidenotes
identifier; bird counting days (monday, tuesday, ...); building chart columns for data context
value; number of birds counted on a day (9, 10, ...); delivering the actual data for inside the chart
separator; colons (:); match the identifiers and values
+++

you see: separators have a pretty important job to do.

let's learn more about them ➡︎

----
##elements of charts:
separators

separators separate identifiers and values.
in our example, we used a colon ~:~ to tell the chart container what is what.
but there are more symbols you can use as separators:

- a colon ~:~
- a comma ~,~
- a semicolon ~;~
- a tab

*they all work the same.*
so for example: if your chart values include commas of their own, you can switch to semicolons as separators in order to get the right result.
just make sure to use only one version per chart.

---
## importing chart data

+++layout:left
there's another reason why we offer a certain variety of separators: this way, you can easily import data from other sources and turn them into a slidenote chart.
just do either of the following:

###import .csv files
click on **file** ![](file.svg) → **import .slidenote, .csv or .md file**.
choose a *.csv* file from your computer → **add as new chart**.

###copy and paste
open your data with the program they are in.
mark the data and hit `ctrl` `c` (mac: `cmd` `c`).
open slidenotes and hit `ctrl` `v` (mac: `cmd` `v`).
mark the data again.
click on the **toolbar button** ![](toolbar.svg) → **+++chart+++**.
+++

----
## different types of data structure

+++layout:left
while importing chart data, you might notice this:
*some sources use other structures than we just did before.*

this is why slidenotes supports two different types:
the **vertical** data structure (which we used before)
and the **horizontal** one.

learning the difference works best with an example. so we're gonna build the *same chart in two different ways*. it's got three identifiers and two values for each. like this and lasts years average temperatures, measured in three months ➡︎
+++

-----
## different types of data structure

+++layout:left
### vertical
each line represents one set of data

+++code
 +++chart
 identifier; value; value
 identifier; value; value
 identifier; value; value
 +++
+++

+++code
 +++chart
 february; 2; 4
 june; 18; 20
 october; 10; 12
 +++
+++
+++

+++layout:right
### horizontal
each column down the lines represents one set of data
+++code
 +++chart
 identifier; identifier; identifier
 value; value; value
 value; value; value
 +++
+++

+++code
 +++chart
 february; june; october
 2; 18; 10
 4; 20; 12
 +++
+++
+++

----
## different types of data structure

it doesn't matter which type you use—both data structures show the same chart:

+++chart:arealine
feb; jun; oct
2; 18; 10
4; 20; 12
+++

## label options

+++layout:left
while building your own charts, you surely noticed that something is missing:
there's a lot of data but no visible context for it all. what we need are labels.

you can insert them by opening a new section inside your chart container.
this section is called **options**.
it sits above the data section and is separated by a ~---~ line.
+++

+++layout:right
+++code
 +++chart
 option section
 all the labels go here
 ---
 data section
 all the data goes here
 +++
+++

let's go and see that in action ➡︎
+++

----
## label options

+++layout:left

+++code:none
   +++chart
   xaxis: months
   yaxis: average temperature in celsius
   dataset1: last year
   dataset2: this year
   ---
   feb; jun; oct
   2; 18; 10
   4; 20; 12
  +++
+++

+++

+++layout:right

+++chart
xaxis: months
yaxis: average temperature in celsius
dataset1: last year
dataset2: this year
---
feb; jun; oct
2; 18; 10
4; 20; 12
+++

+++

----
## label options

+++layout:left
as you can see, you can label:
- the **x-axis**
- the **y-axis**
- the **data sets**

you can also put in a **summary**, which is only accessible for screen readers.
it is meant to offer an alternative text, summarising the charts content in addition to the mere data.
+++

+++layout:right
you don't have to remember every label option by heart.
you can insert them via the **chart context menu** ![](context-menu_chart.svg) which appears on the left side of your data whenever you click anywhere inside your ~+++chart~ container.
you can put them in one by one or all together with an example data set by clicking on **insert example**.
+++
